Package edu.ufp.inf.ManageGraphs

Class PapersGraph<P extends Paper>

java.lang.Object
edu.ufp.inf.ManageGraphs.PapersGraph<P>
Type Parameters:
P - The type of Paper objects stored in the graph.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
public class PapersGraph<P extends Paper> extends Object implements Serializable
A graph representation for papers using an edge-weighted directed graph.

    • listPapersJournalAndTime

      public ArrayList<String> listPapersJournalAndTime(Date start, Date end)
      Lists the titles of papers that are instances of PaperJournal and whose dates fall within the specified time range. Time Complexity: O(n), where n is the number of entries in papersMap. Iterates over each entry in the papersMap to check if it is an instance of PaperJournal and if its date add to result Space Complexity: O(k), where k is the number of papers that are instances of PaperJournal and are within the specified date range.
      Parameters:
      start - The start date of the time range.
      end - The end date of the time range.
      Returns:
      An ArrayList containing the titles of the papers that are of type PaperJournal and fall within the specified time range.

    • calculateFirstOrderQuotes

      public int calculateFirstOrderQuotes(P paper)
      Calculates the first-order quotes (indegree) for a given paper. The first-order quotes represent the number of papers that cite this paper. Time complexity: O(1) adjacency list ExtraSpace: O(1)
      Parameters:
      paper - The paper for which the first-order quotes are to be calculated.
      Returns:
      The number of first-order quotes (indegree) of the given paper. If the paper is not part of the graph (indicated by a graphId of -1), it returns 0.

    • calculateFirstOrderQuotes

      public void calculateFirstOrderQuotes(P paper, String fn)
      Calculates the first-order quotes (indegree) for a given paper and output to a txt file. The first-order quotes represent the number of papers that cite this paper. Time complexity: O(1) adjacency list ExtraSpace: O(1)
      Parameters:
      paper - The paper for which the first-order quotes are to be calculated.
      fn - file name

    • calculateSecondOrderQuotes

      public int calculateSecondOrderQuotes(P paper)
      Calculates the second-order quotes for a given paper. The second-order quotes represent the number of papers that directly cite this paper (first-order quotes) plus the number of papers that cite those citing papers (second-order vertexes). Time Complexity: O(V + E) Extra Space: O(1)
      Parameters:
      paper - The paper for which the second-order quotes are to be calculated.
      Returns:
      The number of second-order quotes of the given paper. If the paper is not part of the graph (indicated by a graphId of -1), it returns 0.

    • calculateSecondOrderQuotes

      public void calculateSecondOrderQuotes(P paper, String fn)
      Calculates the second-order quotes for a given paper and output to a txt file. The second-order quotes represent the number of papers that directly cite this paper (first-order quotes) plus the number of papers that cite those citing papers (second-order vertexes). Time Complexity: O(V + E) Extra Space: O(1)
      Parameters:
      paper - The paper for which the second-order quotes are to be calculated.
      fn - file name

    • selfQuotes

      public int selfQuotes(P paper)
      Calculates the number of self-quotes for a given paper. A self-quote occurs when the citing paper has the same authors as the cited paper. O(E) E = adjacent edges
      Parameters:
      paper - The paper for which the self-quotes are to be calculated.
      Returns:
      The number of self-quotes for the given paper. If the paper is not part of the graph (indicated by a graphId of -1), it returns 0.

      Parameters:

    • dijkstraShortestPath

      public Iterable<Integer> dijkstraShortestPath(P paperStart, P paperEnd)
      Finds the shortest path between two papers using Dijkstra's algorithm. Time Complexity: O((V + E) log V) E = number of edges V = number of vertices Extra Space: O(V)
      Parameters:
      paperStart - The starting paper for the shortest path calculation.
      paperEnd - The ending paper for the shortest path calculation.
      Returns:
      An iterable of paper IDs representing the shortest path from paperStart to paperEnd. If there is no path, it returns null.

    • dijkstraShortestPath

      Finds the shortest path between two papers using Dijkstra's algorithm and output to txt. Time Complexity: O((V + E) log V) E = number of edges V = number of vertices Extra Space: O(V)
      Parameters:

    • subGraphArticleFilter

      public PapersGraph subGraphArticleFilter(String type)
      Filters the papers in the graph based on the provided type. Time Complexity = ( V + E) Extra space = ( V + E) V vertices and E edges the subgraph

      This method creates a subgraph containing papers of a specific type (e.g., PaperConference or PaperJournal) and returns a PapersGraph representing this subgraph.

      The type parameter specifies the type of papers to filter. Valid values are "PaperConference" and "PaperJournal".

      Parameters:
      type - the type of papers to filter
      Returns:
      a PapersGraph representing the subgraph containing papers of the specified type, or null if the subgraph is empty

    • subGraphArticleFilter

      public void subGraphArticleFilter(String type, String fn)
      Filters the papers in the graph based on the provided type. Time Complexity = ( V + E) Extra space = ( V + E) V vertices and E edges the subgraph

      This method creates a subgraph containing papers of a specific type (e.g., PaperConference or PaperJournal) and returns a PapersGraph representing this subgraph.

      The type parameter specifies the type of papers to filter. Valid values are "PaperConference" and "PaperJournal".

      Parameters:
      type - the type of papers to filter
      fn - filename

    • authorQuotesPeriod

      public String authorQuotesPeriod(ArrayList<P> papersList, Date dateStart, Date dateEnd)
      Finds the authors of papers that have been quoted within a specific time period. Time Complexity O(N x E^2) N = number of papers in list E = all edges in the graph
      Parameters:
      papersList - List of papers to check for quotes.
      dateStart - Start date of the period.
      dateEnd - End date of the period.
      Returns:
      A string representation of the authors who have been quoted within the specified period, or a message indicating no quotes were found.
